This article is a Presidential Proclamation by Barack Obama declaring December 7th as National Pearl Harbor Remembrance Day. The proclamation recognizes the surprise attack on Pearl Harbor by Japanese forces on December 7, 1941, and the heroism displayed by those who defended Hawaii. It acknowledges the loss of American lives and the resilience and strength shown by the country in the face of tragedy. The proclamation also honors all those who served in World War II and fought against tyranny and hate. It encourages Americans to observe the day of remembrance and honor the military, past and present, with appropriate ceremonies and activities. The proclamation also urges federal agencies and organizations to fly the flag of the United States at half-staff on December 7th to honor those who died as a result of their service at Pearl Harbor.